{
  "texts": [
    "To overcome the limitations of limited context windows and low usability, empowering LLMs with the agency to actively acquire information and self-correct represents an inevitable trend.",
    "The core principle of this agency is to grant LLMs the ability to interact with and utilize a suite of external software engineering tools.",
    "This capability enables LLMs to interact with external tools in the development lifecycle.As previously discussed in Section 4.1.3, preliminary frameworks for autonomous testing agents have emerged and achieved significant success [69,147].",
    "These agents have demonstrated immense potential by actively seeking information, for example, by interacting with language servers [157], executing fully closed-loop self-improvement cycles formalized in the ReAct paradigm [29], and performing multi-step test planning.However, progressing from these preliminary, task-specific agents to general-purpose testing agents capable of handling industrial-scale complexity, engaging in long-term strategic planning, and adapting to different projects and technology stacks remains a central opportunity for the future.",
    "The key to realizing this vision lies in developing robust middleware that connects LLMs with diverse software engineering toolchains, and enhancing the capabilities of models in longterm planning, memory management, and cross-task generalization."
  ]
}